{"questionId":"22563","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><strong>In this question you will explore some of the properties of special functions <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">f</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">g</mi></math> and their relationship with the trigonometric functions, sine and cosine.</strong></p>\n<p><br>Functions <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> are defined as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>z</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mi>z</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>z</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>z</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mi>z</mi></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>z</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>, where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℂ</mi></math>.</p>\n<p>Consider <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>u</mi></math>, such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>u</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Using <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mrow><mtext>i</mtext><mi>u</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>u</mi><mo>+</mo><mtext>i</mtext><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>u</mi></math>, find expressions, in terms of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>u</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>u</mi></math>, for</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mrow><mtext>i</mtext><mi>u</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mrow><mtext>i</mtext><mi>u</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>u</mi><mo>+</mo><mtext>i</mtext><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>u</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>u</mi><mo>+</mo><mtext>i</mtext><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>u</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>substituting and attempt to simplify&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mtext>i</mtext><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>u</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mtext>i</mtext><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>u</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><br></strong></em><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22563","referenceCode":"21N.3.AHL.TZ0.1c.ii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"giu.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.6—Differentiating polynomials n E Q. Chain, product and quotient rules","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.7—The second derivative","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.3—Graphing","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.6—Simple proof","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.12—Complex numbers – Cartesian form and Argand diag","Topi